                <head>36. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>In a memorandum to the President on July 28, 1961, Secretary of State <persName
                        corresp="#p_RD3">Rusk</persName> set forth details for implementing a new
                    system of foreign economic policy coordination. <persName corresp="#p_RD3"
                        >Rusk</persName> noted that the Council on Foreign Economic Policy had been
                    abolished on March 12 and its functions transferred to the Secretary of State.
                    In a letter to Congress of May 26 transmitting the foreign assistance bill, the
                    President had indicated that he expected the Secretary of State to become the
                    focal point of responsibility for coordination of foreign economic policy, and
                    to choose appropriate mechanisms for carrying this out. Accordingly, <persName
                        corresp="#p_RD3">Rusk</persName> now designated the Under Secretary of State
                    for Economic Affairs to assume responsibility, under <persName corresp="#p_RD3"
                        >Rusk</persName>’s direction, for interagency consultation and coordination
                    of foreign economic policy. <persName corresp="#p_RD3">Rusk</persName>’s
                    memorandum of July 28 to the President is printed in <ref
                        target="frus1961-63v09#d4">
                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1961–1963, volume IX, Document
                        4</ref>.</p>
            </div>
